05557nam a22007815i 9780292769359DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211981txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927693597 a10.7560/7756332doi  a(DE-B1597)588262  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04aThe Sign in Music and Literature /ced. by Wendy Steiner. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1981  a1 online resource (244 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1. Introduction -- t2. The Structure of Semiotic Objects: A Three-Dimensional Model -- t3. How Do We Establish New Codes of Verisimilitude? -- t4. Intratextual Rewriting: Textuality as Language Formation -- t5. Inside Greimas's Square: Literary Characters and Cultural Constraints -- t6. Semantic Oscillation: A Universal of Artistic Expression -- t7. The Literary Artifact -- t8. Typography, Rhymes, and Linguistic Structures in Poetry -- t9. Toward a Semiotics of Music -- t10. Two Views of Musical Semiotics -- t11. Miles Davis Meets Noam Chomsky: Some Observations on Jazz Improvisation and Language Structure -- t12. The Problem of "Ethnic" Perceptions in the Semiotics of Music -- t13. Technique and Signification in the Twelve-Tone Method -- t14. A Musical Icon: Power and Meaning in Javanese Gamelan Music -- t15. Preliminaries to a Semiotics of Ballet -- tBibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe notion of semiotics as a universal language that can encompass any object of perception makes it the focus of a revolutionary field of inquiry, the semiotics of art. This volume represents a unique gathering of semiotic approaches to art: from Saussurian linguistics to transformational grammar, from Prague School aesthetics to Peircean pragmatism, from structuralism to poststructuralism. Though concerned specifically with the semiotics of music and literature, the essays reveal the breadth of semiotics’ interdisciplinary appeal, involving specialists in musicology, ethnomusicology, jazz performance, literary criticism, poetics, aesthetics, rhetoric , linguistics, dance, and film. The diversity of authorial training and approach makes this collection a dramatic demonstration of the on-going debates in the field. In many ways the semiotics of art is the testing ground of sign theory as a whole, and work in this subject is as vital to the interests of theoretical semioticians as to students of the arts. It is to both these interests that this volume is addressed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aAltman, Charles F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArmstrong, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBecker, Alton, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBecker, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlacking, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCervenka, Miroslav, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChatman, Seymour, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenblatt, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHankiss, Elemér, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHrushovski, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeiler, Allan R, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLidov, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOrlov, Henry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerl